T1  - How Vertical Integration Affects Firm Innovation: Quasi-Experimental Evidence
AU  - Zhang, Yuchen
AU  - Tong, Tony W.
Y1  - 2020/10/15
PY  - 2020
DA  - 2021/03/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/orsc.2020.1396
DO  - 10.1287/orsc.2020.1396
T2  - Organization Science
JF  - Organization Science
JO  - Organization Science
SP  - 455
EP  - 479
VL  - 32
IS  - 2
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - Although it is well established that vertical integration decisions have important consequences for firms, direct evidence on how vertical integration matters to firm innovation has been scarce. This study draws from seminal research on organizing for innovation and recent synthesis of transaction cost and capabilities theories to examine how vertical integration affects the rate and types of firm innovation pursued. To strengthen identification of causal effects, we exploit a quasi-experimental design to compare firms that announced and completed a vertical merger and acquisition (M in addition, such firms witness an increase in systemic innovation but a drop in autonomous innovation. Our study contributes important empirical evidence to bear on the literature on the organization of innovation, highlighting that organizational mode choices are a critical determinant of the rate and direction of inventive activity.
AB  - Although it is well established that vertical integration decisions have important consequences for firms, direct evidence on how vertical integration matters to firm innovation has been scarce. This study draws from seminal research on organizing for innovation and recent synthesis of transaction cost and capabilities theories to examine how vertical integration affects the rate and types of firm innovation pursued. To strengthen identification of causal effects, we exploit a quasi-experimental design to compare firms that announced and completed a vertical merger and acquisition (M in addition, such firms witness an increase in systemic innovation but a drop in autonomous innovation. Our study contributes important empirical evidence to bear on the literature on the organization of innovation, highlighting that organizational mode choices are a critical determinant of the rate and direction of inventive activity.
